1
00:00:01,189 --> 00:00:05,230
Over the last few years, supply and demand
trading has become one of the most popular

2
00:00:05,230 --> 00:00:06,390
trading strategies.

3
00:00:06,390 --> 00:00:11,280
And for good reason because this trading style
takes the best of support and resistance and

4
00:00:11,280 --> 00:00:13,480
adds the concept of supply and demand.

5
00:00:13,480 --> 00:00:17,990
The result is a strategy that allows you to
pinpoint where the banks are buying and selling,

6
00:00:17,990 --> 00:00:22,540
giving you the chance to get into some of
the biggest reversals BEFORE they begin.

7
00:00:22,540 --> 00:00:26,630
In today’s video, I'm going to give you
a full breakdown of how to correctly find

8
00:00:26,630 --> 00:00:30,960
and draw supply and demand zones and the common
mistakes you should avoid when trading these

9
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:33,329
areas.

10
00:00:33,329 --> 00:00:38,149
News events, economic announcements, and just
general market action all cause different

11
00:00:38,149 --> 00:00:43,379
groups of traders to buy and sell, resulting
in changes to the supply and demand equation.

12
00:00:43,379 --> 00:00:48,489
These changes manifest visually as the rises,
declines, and consolidations we see on our

13
00:00:48,489 --> 00:00:49,730
charts.

14
00:00:49,730 --> 00:00:53,420
When we see price rising, demand outweighs
supply.

15
00:00:53,420 --> 00:00:56,719
When we see price falling, supply outweighs
demand.

16
00:00:56,719 --> 00:01:02,600
When supply and demand are in relative balance,
a consolidation forms.

17
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:06,960
Changes in supply and demand will ONLY OCCUR
when the banks and other big traders buy or

18
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:07,960
sell.

19
00:01:07,960 --> 00:01:12,440
We, retail traders, can't cause price to rise
or fall because we don't have enough money!

20
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:16,910
Only the banks, with their high buying/selling
power, can make price move.

21
00:01:16,910 --> 00:01:21,790
In Forex for example, the banks can never
place their full position all at once.

22
00:01:21,790 --> 00:01:26,970
Their positions are so large they must break
them into smaller chunks and place each trade

23
00:01:26,970 --> 00:01:31,860
individually, around a similar price, to avoid
pushing price away and potentially forcing

24
00:01:31,860 --> 00:01:33,790
the entry at a bad price.

25
00:01:33,790 --> 00:01:38,920
This way they achieve the same effect of placing
one huge position, by placing a bunch of small

26
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:40,530
ones instead.

27
00:01:40,530 --> 00:01:45,290
But, here's the banks’ problem:
These positions are often so big that not

28
00:01:45,290 --> 00:01:49,520
enough people exist on the opposite side to
get them placed - buying when the banks want

29
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:54,270
to sell, or selling when the banks want to
buy, even if they convert their positions

30
00:01:54,270 --> 00:01:55,560
into smaller chunks.

31
00:01:55,560 --> 00:02:00,950
So, they must let price move away and then
make it return later on to get the rest of

32
00:02:00,950 --> 00:02:02,320
their position entered.

33
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:06,970
Now, supply and demand trading is all about
finding points where the banks have bought

34
00:02:06,970 --> 00:02:12,390
or sold and then jumping into trades when
price returns to pick up the rest of the banks’

35
00:02:12,390 --> 00:02:17,590
position to get into the reversal, right beside
the banks.

36
00:02:17,590 --> 00:02:21,640
Supply and demand trading is a method where
the idea is to find points in the market where

37
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:26,700
the price has made a strong advance or decline
and mark these areas as supply and demand

38
00:02:26,700 --> 00:02:28,950
zones using rectangles.

39
00:02:28,950 --> 00:02:33,660
The point in which the price has made a strong
advance is marked by the trader as a demand

40
00:02:33,660 --> 00:02:34,720
zone.

41
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:40,030
Demand Zones represent points where the banks
have placed a significant number of buy positions.

42
00:02:40,030 --> 00:02:43,470
These are the support levels of supply and
demand trading, if you will.

43
00:02:43,470 --> 00:02:48,370
A point where the market has made a sharp
decline is marked as a supply zone.

44
00:02:48,370 --> 00:02:53,620
These are points where the banks place a significant
number of sell positions and these are resistance

45
00:02:53,620 --> 00:02:56,540
points where price could fall.

46
00:02:56,540 --> 00:02:59,390
Now, how to find and draw supply and demand
zones.

47
00:02:59,390 --> 00:03:04,530
If you want to be successful trading supply
and demand, you MUST master the finding of

48
00:03:04,530 --> 00:03:08,569
high probability zones and correctly drawing
them on the chart.

49
00:03:08,569 --> 00:03:12,180
It takes time, practice, and experience to
get this right.

50
00:03:12,180 --> 00:03:16,300
The most important rule is to look for sharp
rises and declines in price.

51
00:03:16,300 --> 00:03:21,849
They reveal the banks are buying or selling,
which means a supply or, a demand, must exist

52
00:03:21,849 --> 00:03:25,740
at the source of the rise or decline.

53
00:03:25,740 --> 00:03:30,959
Supply zones can be located by looking for
a swift drop away from either a single candle

54
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:35,330
or small consolidation structure (commonly
known as a base).

55
00:03:35,330 --> 00:03:41,410
The base consists of a few candlesticks in
a tight sideways range (consolidation).

56
00:03:41,410 --> 00:03:46,130
This is an example of a supply zone formed
with a base.

57
00:03:46,130 --> 00:03:51,360
And this is an example of a supply zone formed
from a single candle.

58
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:55,680
Demand zones are found when the market makes
a large move up from a single candle or a

59
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:56,680
base.

60
00:03:56,680 --> 00:04:00,560
Here is an example of a demand zone created
from a single candle.

61
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:05,129
And here is an example of a demand zone with
a base.

62
00:04:05,129 --> 00:04:08,380
And here is a first important point.

63
00:04:08,380 --> 00:04:13,790
The strength of the movement away from supply
or demand zone is not a determining factor

64
00:04:13,790 --> 00:04:15,680
in how strong the zone is.

65
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:21,780
As long as a zone has at least one large bullish
or bearish candle moving away from it’s

66
00:04:21,780 --> 00:04:26,210
considered just as valid for trading as a
zone which has a significant move away from

67
00:04:26,210 --> 00:04:27,210
it.

68
00:04:27,210 --> 00:04:30,280
And here’s another important tip.

69
00:04:30,280 --> 00:04:35,160
Supply or demand zones which are formed from
a base tend to result in more successful trades

70
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:38,340
than zones which form from a single candle.

71
00:04:38,340 --> 00:04:42,300
This is due to the sensitive nature of the
psychology of the traders who had trading

72
00:04:42,300 --> 00:04:44,720
positions back when the base was created.

73
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:49,810
A zone which forms with a single candle means
not a lot of traders were caught on the wrong

74
00:04:49,810 --> 00:04:54,900
side of the market before the market moved
up or down creating the supply or demand zone.

75
00:04:54,900 --> 00:05:00,840
A zone with a base contains far more trapped
traders because the market was moving sideways

76
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:05,570
in a consolidation before it began advancing
higher or falling lower.

77
00:05:05,570 --> 00:05:10,380
And when the market returns to a zone formed
from a base the traders who were trapped either

78
00:05:10,380 --> 00:05:15,020
long or short (depending on the zones) will
begin closing their trades.

79
00:05:15,020 --> 00:05:17,460
And this creates liquidity in the market.

80
00:05:17,460 --> 00:05:22,490
Now we know how to find and locate supply
and demand zones on our charts, we need to

81
00:05:22,490 --> 00:05:24,490
actually draw the zones.

82
00:05:24,490 --> 00:05:29,430
Both single candle supply and demand zones
and zones with a base are drawn in the same

83
00:05:29,430 --> 00:05:30,430
way.

84
00:05:30,430 --> 00:05:34,270
There are many different methods of how to
draw the zones properly, but I will share

85
00:05:34,270 --> 00:05:37,080
the one I found to be the most consistent
to me.

86
00:05:37,080 --> 00:05:39,350
We will begin by drawing a supply zone.

87
00:05:39,350 --> 00:05:45,520
You always draw supply zones from the last
BULLISH candle before the drop, if the candle

88
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:50,120
immediately before the drop is bearish, then
you need to locate the most recent bullish

89
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:52,639
candle and draw the zone accordingly.

90
00:05:52,639 --> 00:05:57,400
So the open of the bullish candle is where
you want to begin drawing your supply zone

91
00:05:57,400 --> 00:05:58,400
from.

92
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:03,270
Once you’ve done this you need to drag the
rectangle up to the most recent high before

93
00:06:03,270 --> 00:06:05,660
the drop.

94
00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:17,800
Here are several examples of supply zones.

95
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:32,850
For demand zones, we draw the zone from the
most recent BEARISH candle found immediately

96
00:06:32,850 --> 00:06:35,240
before the up move creating the zone.

97
00:06:35,240 --> 00:06:40,419
In this example you can see I’ve drawn the
demand zone from the open of the bearish candle

98
00:06:40,419 --> 00:06:43,500
found just before the market made its move
up.

99
00:06:43,500 --> 00:06:48,600
From here you need to find the most recent
low nearest the zone and drag your rectangle

100
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:53,370
to the low, now you have the demand zone drawn
on your charts.

101
00:06:53,370 --> 00:07:15,600
Here are several examples of demand zones.

102
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:20,130
In contrast to when we are drawing supply
zones, the candle you’re drawing the demand

103
00:07:20,130 --> 00:07:21,430
zone off must be bearish.

104
00:07:21,430 --> 00:07:26,340
If it happens to be bullish you need to go
back and locate the nearest bearish candle

105
00:07:26,340 --> 00:07:30,220
before the move up and draw your rectangle
from there.

106
00:07:30,220 --> 00:07:34,150
The reason why this is important is due to
how the banks place trades.

107
00:07:34,150 --> 00:07:38,660
Banks do not place trades onto movements which
are in the direction of the trade they are

108
00:07:38,660 --> 00:07:39,660
placing.

109
00:07:39,660 --> 00:07:45,490
In simple terms, if the current candle is
bullish the banks wont be placing buy trades,

110
00:07:45,490 --> 00:07:48,669
if its bearish, they wont be placing sell
trades.

111
00:07:48,669 --> 00:07:54,150
Before you start trading Supply and Demand,
there are 2 key rules you need to understand

112
00:07:54,150 --> 00:07:59,699
to find the right zones on the chart and trade
them correctly using your entry method.

113
00:07:59,699 --> 00:08:02,949
First rule is that old zones rarely work.

114
00:08:02,949 --> 00:08:07,669
Apparently, the longer the market has been
away from a supply or demand zone the better

115
00:08:07,669 --> 00:08:11,889
chance the market has of turning when it eventually
returns.

116
00:08:11,889 --> 00:08:13,870
This is completely wrong.

117
00:08:13,870 --> 00:08:16,400
Recent zones are far more important.

118
00:08:16,400 --> 00:08:21,139
If we compare the old supply and demand zones
(colored blue), with the more recent zones

119
00:08:21,139 --> 00:08:26,509
colored white, its easy to see how trading
zones which have been created recently are

120
00:08:26,509 --> 00:08:32,430
far more effective than trading zones which
were created a long time ago.

121
00:08:32,430 --> 00:08:36,419
Second rule is to trade only fresh/untouched
zones.

122
00:08:36,419 --> 00:08:40,690
Another big misconception you'll hear in the
supply and demand community is the idea that

123
00:08:40,690 --> 00:08:45,820
supply and demand zones have the power to
cause reversals more than once, like support

124
00:08:45,820 --> 00:08:47,540
and resistance levels do.

125
00:08:47,540 --> 00:08:49,250
Again, this isn't true.

126
00:08:49,250 --> 00:08:52,230
Supply and demand zones are ONE TIME USE.

127
00:08:52,230 --> 00:08:55,550
Not two times or three times, one time ONLY.

128
00:08:55,550 --> 00:09:00,370
When price hits a zone and reverses, that's
it; the zone loses its power.

129
00:09:00,370 --> 00:09:04,670
The probability it'll cause another reversal
in the future is low.

130
00:09:04,670 --> 00:09:09,790
The only exception to this rule is if a zone
forms at the top or bottom of a consolidation.

131
00:09:09,790 --> 00:09:14,830
In this case, price will probably reverse
two or three times from the zone, since the

132
00:09:14,830 --> 00:09:19,060
consolidation shows the banks are buying/selling
from similar points.

133
00:09:19,060 --> 00:09:24,380
However, once the consolidation is over, the
zone loses all its power and probably won't

134
00:09:24,380 --> 00:09:26,380
cause another reversal.

135
00:09:26,380 --> 00:09:31,770
Now, this was an introduction to supply and
demand trading and it was impossible for me

136
00:09:31,770 --> 00:09:35,700
to cover everything about supply and demand
trading in this one video.

137
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:39,890
